# Concurrency and parallelism

- Distinguish I/O-bound (async, threads) from CPU-bound (processes, thread pools) workloads.
- Prefer async/await for I/O-heavy services; avoid blocking calls inside async contexts.
- Use bounded thread/process pools — unbounded concurrency exhausts memory and connections.
- Protect shared mutable state with locks, channels, or actor patterns — never assume thread safety.
- Set timeouts on all concurrent operations (HTTP, DB, queue consumers).
- Use backpressure: slow producers when consumers lag (queue limits, semaphores).
- Parallelize independent tasks; serialize tasks with shared dependencies.
- Avoid deadlocks: acquire locks in consistent order; prefer lock-free structures when simple.
- Test concurrent code with race detectors and load tests, not unit tests alone.
- Log correlation IDs across concurrent requests for debugging.
